[Bovine anthrax is regularly reported in Central Province, possibly because it was close to the major laboratory in Nairobi, but latterly it clearly has a competent diagnostic laboratory within the province: 2005 (4 outbreaks), 2006 (16), 2007 (10 in cattle, 3 in swine), 2008 (6), 2009 (8 in cattle, 3 in small ruminants with one mixed, and 3 in pigs (one mixed), 2010 (13 outbreaks with one involving cattle, sheep and pigs, plus one just sheep), 2011 (4 in cattle, and 3 in pigs), 2012 (4 in cattle, one in sheep, 2 in pigs). There have been Central Province human cases reported, sometimes with deaths, in 2009 and 2010. It is very revealing that the owner told her local veterinary officer about her concerns with this sick cow. There was a level of trust involved, which is good.

This event points up a central problem, that even though the vaccine is extremely cheap, it can be a financial challenge to local farmers. And as they prevaricate, animals die. Kenyans are not alone in this, unfortunately.

For a map of Kenya, go to: http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/africa/kenya.gif. To find Murang'a, go to: http://www.fallingrain.com/world/KE/01/Muranga.html. - Mod.MHJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1zkN.]
